   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:10` – the reverse‑print loop declares
   `size_t i` and tests `i >= 0`. Because `size_t` is unsigned, when `v.size()`
   is `0` the expression `v.size()‑1` wraps to the maximum value, so the
   condition is always true; the loop never terminates and on the next iteration
   it reads `v[i]` past the vector’s end, causing an out‑of‑bounds read that
   ASan reports as a container‑overflow and otherwise results in an infinite
   hang.
   
   LOCAL FIX: replace the faulty loop with a version that cannot underflow. One
   minimal edit is:
   
   ```diff
   -    for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
   -        std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
   -    }
   +    for (int i = static_cast<int>(v.size()) - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
   +        std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
   +    }
   ```
   
   This uses a signed loop variable, so the termination condition correctly
   becomes false once `i` reaches `‑1`, eliminating the overflow and the
   associated OOB access.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: adopt a design that eliminates raw unsigned index arithmetic in
   reverse iteration throughout the codebase, for example by requiring all
   reverse loops to use `std::reverse_iterator` (or a range‑based reverse view)
   and by adding a clang‑tidy check that flags the pattern `for (size_t i = ...;
   i >= 0; ...)`; this prevents the entire class of underflow‑induced infinite
   loops and container‑overflows by enforcing safer traversal idioms at the API
   level.
